    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "That's a good start. Some of my more skeptical students might ask, though, why we call it 'substantive' instead of just 'procedural.' Can you add a part to that explanation that explains why the 'substantive' side is the more important or accurate way to look at the Constitution's intent regarding liberty?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Here's the revised explanation:\n\n Substantive due process refers to the core idea that certain rights, such as freedom of speech, freedom of assembly, and equal protection under the law, are fundamental to a free and democratic society. This concept has been a vital tool for protecting civil rights and personal liberties throughout American history, as seen in landmark cases like Plessy v. Ferguson (challenging segregation laws) and Griswold v. Connecticut (protecting individual rights to contraception). What sets substantive due process apart is that it focuses on the underlying principles and values of the Constitution, rather than just the procedures set out in the document. In other words, it looks at whether a law is \"repugnant to the Constitution\" (requiring it to be fundamentally incompatible with liberty) rather than just following a specific procedure, which is more related to the concept of procedural due process. This distinction acknowledges that the Constitution's framers intended to protect fundamental rights and liberties, rather than just follow a set of technical rules.",
      "source": "target",
